In view of the great probability of the haemopyrroline formula as given above, and having started synthetical experiments with the view to prepare artificially haemopyrroline at the same time as Kuster‚ and in any case independently from this author, we have decide to test the said formula by a method ‘differing from the one followed up by Kflster. The preparation of methyl-n-propyl-maleic anhydridc does not offer any difficulties: propylacetoacetic ether is condensed with prussic acid. the product obtained saponified and the methyl-propyl malic acid produced distilled. The reaction takes place smoothly, exactly in accordance with other similar synthesis described by Michael and Tissot. The properties of the anhydride agree in general with the description given by Kflster and Haas and we may pass over at present any details, The imide we obtained by prolonged heating of the anhydride with alcoholic ammonia to 110⁰. Whereas Kaster and Haas describe crystalls of this substance we never were so fortunate as to get it in the crystalline state. The imide we tried to convert into haemopyrroline in exactly the same *manner as Bell converted succinic imide into pyrroline‚ viz. we heated it with a large excess of zinc dust in the pre- sence of hydrogen. There distilled very-soon a thick liquid which possessed a smell similar to that of haemopyrmline, and which on being treated with diluted hydroehloric aeid dissolved partly, leaving a brown, greasy substance behind.
